    <item>
      <title>Random access memories: Inside the time-shifting narrative of The Wreck</title>
      <link>https://n-kase.github.io/rss/posts/post-501/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 15 Jun 2026 18:56:03 +0900</pubDate>
      
      <guid>https://n-kase.github.io/rss/posts/post-501/</guid>
      <description>&lt;![CDATA[<h2 id="aiによる要約">AIによる要約
</h2><p>この記事では、個人的な事故体験を基にしたビデオゲーム『The Wreck』の開発背景とその独自のストーリーテリング手法が紹介されており、ゲームが従来のエンターテイメントの枠を超えて、深い感情や記憶を掘り下げるメディアとして機能し得ることを示している。こうした試みは、プレイヤーや業界に対してゲームを単なる遊びではなく、現実の物語を共有する芸術形式として再評価させ、より物語中心で内省的な作品が増える可能性を示唆している。したがって、開発者は個人の経験を素直に反映させ、プレイヤーに共感を呼ぶストーリー重視のデザインを追求すべきであり、プレイヤー側もゲームを多様な表現手段の一つとして受け入れる姿勢が求められる。</p>
<h2 id="和訳本文">和訳本文
</h2><h2 id="random-access-memories-inside-the-time-shifting-narrative-of-the-wreck">Random access memories: Inside the time-shifting narrative of The Wreck
</h2><p>May 6, 2025</p>
<p><img alt="The main character of The Wreck, a writer named Junon, is seen in animated form standing in a hospital hallway. The top half of the halls are a salmon color and the bottom half are a dingy white tile. Junon is wearing a black sweatshirt and black glasses and looking at the camera." loading="lazy" sizes="(max-width: 767px) calc(100vw - 30px), (max-width: 1023px) 700px, (max-width: 1279px) 950px, 1232px" src="/rss/downloaded_images/129e6a9f2de4242aff48440d0d3283d0.jpeg"></p>
<p><em>The Wreck</em> はゲームジャンルに分類されるが、ビジュアルノベル、インタラクティブ体験、プレイ可能な映画とも呼ばれている。フローレント・マウリンはそれをすべて受け入れている。「私たちは謙虚に、ビデオゲームが何であるかという考えを広げる一助になれればいいと思っている」と語る。</p>
<p>マウリンは <em>The Wreck</em> の共同脚本家、デザイナー、プロデューサーであり、ここでは読者自身に何と呼ぶかを決めてもらう。 <em>The Wreck</em> は、母親に関する人生を変える決断を迫られるために突然病院に呼ばれた作家・ジュノンの物語を描く。物語の核は、ゲームタイトルにもなった事故だが、その後のストーリーは断片的になり、プレイヤーが見かけ上つながりのないシーンを複数の視点から何度も見ることで形になっていく。<em>The Wreck</em> は軽いものではないが、力強いストーリーと型破りなメカニクスが組み合わさり、唯一無二の体験を生み出している。</p>
<p>「私たちは beaten path（常識的な道）から少し外れたゲームを作ろうとした」と語るマウリンは、The Pixel Hunt スタジオの社長兼CEOでもある。「 hopefully it connects with people（人々の心に届けばいい）」と付け加えた。</p>
<p>ADA FACT SHEET</p>
<p><img alt="In this screenshot from The Wreck, the main character, Junon, walks away from a kitchen that’s on fire. Behind her, flames erupt from the stove and sink area." loading="lazy" sizes="(max-width: 767px) calc(100vw - 30px), (max-width: 1023px) 700px, (max-width: 1279px) 950px, 1232px" src="/rss/downloaded_images/61993131c44f8776d6eb6aabe2270132.jpeg"></p>
<h3 id="the-wreck">The Wreck
</h3><ul>
<li>**Winner:**Social impact</li>
<li>**Team:**The Pixel Hunt</li>
<li>**Available on:**iPhone, iPad</li>
<li>**Team size:**4</li>
</ul>
<p>マウリンは元々フランスの児童ジャーナリストで、雑誌や新聞で約10年働いた後、ビデオゲームに転向した。現実の人々の実際の物語を共有する別の手段としてゲームを見たからだ。「現実は映画、小説、漫画のインスピレーション源だが、ゲームの世界ではほとんど存在しない」と彼は言う。「それを変えたかった。」</p>
<p>2014年に設立された The Pixel Hunt は、App Store Award を受賞した歴史アドベンチャー <em>Inua</em> や、テキストメッセージ形式のアドベンチャー <em>Bury Me, My Love</em> といった評価の高いタイトルをリリースしている。後者の開発終盤で、マウリンと娘は重大な自動車事故に巻き込まれた。</p>
<p>「正直、映画のワンカットみたいだった」とマウリンは言う。「時間がゆっくり流れ、その瞬間とは無関係な奇妙な記憶が頭をよぎった。後で読んだところによると、脳はそうした状況に対処するために過去の記憶をあさって関連知見を探すそうだ。それは突然かつ激しく、私はそれに何かを残したいと思った。すぐに頭に浮かんだのは、ゲームを作ることだった。」</p>
<p><img alt="In this screenshot from The Wreck, a nurse with black hair wearing blue scrubs talks to the main character, Junon, in a hospital hallway. Dialogue on the screen says, “Why do you think I’m here?” “I’m sorry.”" loading="lazy" sizes="(max-width: 767px) calc(100vw - 30px), (max-width: 1023px) 700px, (max-width: 1279px) 950px, 1232px" src="/rss/downloaded_images/efef27d23932a1bc1a068ce429669131.jpeg"></p>
<p>ジュノンと病院スタッフのやり取りが <em>The Wreck</em> の物語を動かす。</p>
<p>しかしマウリンは出典に近すぎた；事故が彼に深い影響を残し、彼は創作プロセスから距離を置いた。「あの感情の強さから自分を守ろうとしていたんだと思う」と彼は言う。「そのとき、アートディレクターのアレックスがこう言った。『これは君のアイデアだ。君が本当に掘り下げて創作方針を握らないと、花開かないよ。』そして彼は正しかった。」</p>
<p>言及したアートディレクターはアレクサンドル・グリレッタで、リード開発者のホレース・リブート、アニメーターのペギー・ルコーヴェ、サウンドデザイナーのルイスとラファエル・トーレス、そして執筆中に「第二の脳」として機能したマウリンの姉・コラリーとともに開発チームを率いた。（興味深い偶然だが、ゲームの脚本は Inkle が開発したオープンソースのスクリプト言語で書かれており、同じ言語は 2022 年の Apple Design Award 受賞作 <em>Overboard</em> でも使われている。）</p>
<p><img alt="In this screenshot from The Wreck, a woman with short blonde hair is sitting in a softly lit room. She is saying, “So what’s the play? Idiot or goldfish?”" loading="lazy" sizes="(max-width: 767px) calc(100vw - 30px), (max-width: 1023px) 700px, (max-width: 1279px) 950px, 1232px" src="/rss/downloaded_images/b1108f177f8d8d62c8f9b672fbb89021.jpeg"></p>
<p>ジュノンの姉は <em>The Wreck</em> で必ずしも歓迎される存在ではないかもしれない。</p>
<p><em>The Wreck</em> の物語は二つのパートに分かれている。まずチームが「ラストデイ」と呼ぶ最初のパートでは、ジュノンが母親の状況に直面しながら病院におり、姉や元夫との関わりが明らかになる。マウリンによると、「ラストデイ」は設計の観点から見てかなりシンプルだった。「映画的な見た目にしたかった」と彼は言う。「だからストーリーボードのように見せ、ストップモーションアニメーションとフレーミングを加えた。別に凝ったことはしていない。本当に難しかったのは記憶の部分だ。」</p>
<p>それらの「記憶」―そしてそれを通じて語られるバックストーリー―は、プレイヤーがシーンを映画のように見つつ、早送りや巻き</p>
<hr>
<h2 id="元スレッド記事本文">元スレッド・記事本文
</h2><h2 id="random-access-memories-inside-the-time-shifting-narrative-of-the-wreck-1">Random access memories: Inside the time-shifting narrative of The Wreck
</h2><p>May 6, 2025</p>
<p><img alt="The main character of The Wreck, a writer named Junon, is seen in animated form standing in a hospital hallway. The top half of the halls are a salmon color and the bottom half are a dingy white tile. Junon is wearing a black sweatshirt and black glasses and looking at the camera." loading="lazy" sizes="(max-width: 767px) calc(100vw - 30px), (max-width: 1023px) 700px, (max-width: 1279px) 950px, 1232px" src="/rss/downloaded_images/129e6a9f2de4242aff48440d0d3283d0.jpeg"></p>
<p><em>The Wreck</em> is filed under games, but it’s also been called a visual novel, an interactive experience, and a playable movie. Florent Maurin is OK with all of it. “I like to think we’re humbly participating in expanding the idea of what a video game can be,” he says.</p>
<p>Maurin is the co-writer, designer, and producer of <em>The Wreck</em> — and here we’ll let you decide what to call it. <em>The Wreck</em> tells the tale of Junon, a writer who’s abruptly called to a hospital to make a life-changing decision involving her mother. The story is anchored by the accident that lends the game its name, but the ensuing narrative is splintered, and begins to take shape only as players navigate through seemingly disconnected scenes that can be viewed multiple times from different perspectives. <em>The Wreck</em> is far from light. But its powerful story and unorthodox mechanics combine for a unique experience.</p>
<p>“We tried to make a game that’s a bit off the beaten path,” says Maurin, who’s also the president and CEO of The Pixel Hunt studio, “and hopefully it connects with people.”</p>
<p>ADA FACT SHEET</p>
<p><img alt="In this screenshot from The Wreck, the main character, Junon, walks away from a kitchen that’s on fire. Behind her, flames erupt from the stove and sink area." loading="lazy" sizes="(max-width: 767px) calc(100vw - 30px), (max-width: 1023px) 700px, (max-width: 1279px) 950px, 1232px" src="/rss/downloaded_images/61993131c44f8776d6eb6aabe2270132.jpeg"></p>
<h3 id="the-wreck-1">The Wreck
</h3><ul>
<li>**Winner:**Social impact</li>
<li>**Team:**The Pixel Hunt</li>
<li>**Available on:**iPhone, iPad</li>
<li>**Team size:**4</li>
</ul>
<p>Maurin is a former children’s journalist who worked at magazines and newspapers in his native France. After nearly 10 years in the field, he pivoted to video games, seeing them as a different way to share real stories about real people. “Reality is a source of inspiration in movies, novels, and comic books, but it’s almost completely absent in the gaming landscape,” he says. “We wanted to challenge that.”</p>
<p>Founded in 2014, The Pixel Hunt has released acclaimed titles like the App Store Award–winning historical adventure <em>Inua</em> and the text-message adventure <em>Bury Me, My Love</em>. It was near the end of the development process for the latter that Maurin and his daughter were involved in a serious car accident.</p>
<p>“It was honestly like a movie trope,” he says. “Time slowed down. Weird memories that had nothing to do with the moment flashed before my eyes. Later I read that the brain parses through old memories to find relevant knowledge for facing that kind of situation. It was so sudden and so intense, and I knew I wanted to make something of it. And what immediately came to mind was a game.”</p>
<p><img alt="In this screenshot from The Wreck, a nurse with black hair wearing blue scrubs talks to the main character, Junon, in a hospital hallway. Dialogue on the screen says, “Why do you think I’m here?” “I’m sorry.”" loading="lazy" sizes="(max-width: 767px) calc(100vw - 30px), (max-width: 1023px) 700px, (max-width: 1279px) 950px, 1232px" src="/rss/downloaded_images/efef27d23932a1bc1a068ce429669131.jpeg"></p>
<p>Junon&rsquo;s interactions with the hospital staff drive the narrative in <em>The Wreck</em>.</p>
<p>But Maurin was too close to the source material; the accident had left a lasting impact, and he separated himself from the creative process. “I think I was trying to protect myself from the intensity of that feeling,” he says. “That’s when Alex, our art director, told me, ‘Look, this is your idea, and I don’t think it’ll bloom if you don’t really dig deep and own the creative direction.’ And he was right.”</p>
<p>That was art director Alexandre Grilletta, who helmed the development team alongside lead developer Horace Ribout, animator Peggy Lecouvey, sound designers Luis and Rafael Torres, and Maurin’s sister, Coralie, who served as a “second brain” during writing. (In a nice bit of serendipity, the game’s script was written in an open-source scripting language developed by Inkle, which used it for their own Apple Design Award-winning game, <em>Overboard</em>, in 2022.)</p>
<p><img alt="In this screenshot from The Wreck, a woman with short blonde hair is sitting in a softly lit room. She is saying, “So what’s the play? Idiot or goldfish?”" loading="lazy" sizes="(max-width: 767px) calc(100vw - 30px), (max-width: 1023px) 700px, (max-width: 1279px) 950px, 1232px" src="/rss/downloaded_images/b1108f177f8d8d62c8f9b672fbb89021.jpeg"></p>
<p>Junon&rsquo;s sister might not be an entirely welcome presence in <em>The Wreck</em>.</p>
<p>The story of <em>The Wreck</em> is split into two parts. The first — what the team calls the “last day” — follows Junon at the hospital while she faces her mother’s situation as well as revealing interactions with her sister and ex-husband. Maurin says the “last day” was pretty straightforward from a design standpoint. “We knew we wanted a cinematic look,” he says, “so we made it look like a storyboard with some stop-motion animation and framing. It was really nothing too fancy. The part that was way more challenging was the memories.”</p>
<p>Those “memories” — and the backstory they tell — employ a clever mechanism in which players view a scene as a movie and have the ability to fast-forward or rewind the scene. These memory scenes feel much different; they’re dreamlike and inventive, with swooping camera angles, shifting perspectives, and words that float in the air. “I saw that first in <em>What Remains of Edith Finch</em>,” says Maurin. “I thought it was an elegant way of suggesting the thing that triggers a character’s brain in that moment.”</p>
<p><img alt="The main character of The Wreck, a writer named Junon, is seen in animated form standing in a hospital hallway. She is wearing a black sweatshirt and black rimmed glasses. Three shimmering phrases float in the air around her: “impacts the body,” “impaired,” and “long-term.”" loading="lazy" sizes="(max-width: 767px) calc(100vw - 30px), (max-width: 1023px) 700px, (max-width: 1279px) 950px, 1232px" src="/rss/downloaded_images/1e9fdac4798bf8622a93f8ac758b90be.jpeg"></p>
<p>Junon&rsquo;s thoughts are often conveyed in floating phrases that surround her in stressful moments.</p>
<p>Successive viewings of these memories can reveal new details or cast doubt on their legitimacy — something Maurin wrote from experience. “I’ll give you an example,” he says. “When my parents brought my baby sister home from the hospital, I remember the exact moment they arrived in the car. It’s incredibly vivid. But the weird part is: This memory is in the third person. I see myself tiptoeing to the window to watch them in the street — which is impossible! I rewrote my own memory for some reason, and only my brain knows why it works like that. But it feels so real.”</p>
<p>Throughout the development process, Maurin and team held close to the idea of a “moving and mature” story. In fact, early prototypes of <em>The Wreck</em> were more gamified — in one version, players grabbed floating items — but playtesters found the activity distracting. “It took them out of the story,” Maurin says. “It broke the immersion. And that was counterproductive to our goal.”</p>
<p><img alt="This screenshot from The Wreck depicts a car accident taking place from inside the vehicle. A blue tin labeled “Sparrow Peppermints” is flying through the air. Outside the windshield, the bright light of a fire can be seen." loading="lazy" sizes="(max-width: 767px) calc(100vw - 30px), (max-width: 1023px) 700px, (max-width: 1279px) 950px, 1232px" src="/rss/downloaded_images/355666a38c8ab7101ab5bdc6c6da6017.jpeg"></p>
<p>Items in <em>The Wreck</em> — like this tin of peppermints — often carry a larger meaning.</p>
<p>Maurin admits that approaching games with this mindset can be a challenge. “Some players are curious about our games and absolutely love them. Some people think, ‘These don’t fit the perception of what I think I enjoy.’ And maybe the games are for them, and maybe they’re not. But this is what we’ve been doing for 11 years. And I think we&rsquo;re getting better at it.”</p>
<p>[Meet the 2024 Apple Design Award winners]</p>
<p>&hellip;（長文のため省略されました）</p>
]]></description>
